The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro

 The City Diary

 Engineers of the Calcutta Environment Improvement Project (CEIP) met the state irrigation department engineers on Thursday to discuss measures to prevent waterlogging in parts of Tollygunge and the added area in Behala during monsoon. Eight wards in the two areas have been identified as prone to waterlogging. Both the CEIP and the irrigation department engineers decided to take up the matter with the Metro Railway authorities. Metro Railways extension work at Kudghat has hampered upgrade of drainage facilities.

 Chinnapally Rangarao, 48, was arrested in Vijaywada on Thursday for allegedly cheating a Burrabazar-based company of Rs 15.5 lakh. According to police, Rangarao worked for a company that received a large consignment of silk saris from Burrabazar-based Venkateswar Creations. Rangarao had allegedly refused to pay for the consignment. 

 A new platform (platform no. 22) was inaugurated at Howrah stations new complex on Thursday by Union minister of state for railways R. Velu. The parliamentary affairs minister, the mayor of Howrah, and MLA Lagan Deo Singh were present at the function. 

 A first-class coach has been added to the Sealdah-Lalgola-Sealdah passenger train, replacing a general second-class coach, said an Eastern Railway spokesperson on Thursday.

 Thai Airways on Thursday launched an offer for business-class passengers. Under the offer, the passengers can take along their spouse, business partner or friend for free. The offer is valid till May 15 on the Calcutta-Bangkok-Calcutta route. SpiceJet also announced a scheme, under which every 99th passenger will win a free ticket. The offer is valid till April 15.

 Two cars were gutted in a fire at Regent Park on Thursday evening. Fire brigade sources said that two tenders took about an hour to control the blaze. The cause of fire is yet to be ascertained. The cars were impounded by the detective department of police.

 Aloke Das, 32, a material supplier to the West Bengal State Electricity Board, was electrocuted at Nodakhali, on the sourthern fringes, on Thursday afternoon. Police said he touched a live wire near his house. The body has been sent for post-mortem.

 Governor Gopalkrishna Gandhi inaugurated a park, named after late Jayanta Bhattacharya, on Thursday. Bhattacharya had worked on the Ganga-cleaning project. The governor assured that steps will be taken to preserve the river.

 A health meet was organised by the Association of Health Service at Rabindra Bhavan, Barasat, on Thursday. Issues like infrastructure crunch in government hospitals were discussed. 

 A workshop on the science of living was held at Don Bosco School, Liluah, on Tuesday.

